<subsection><title>What Is a Square Root?</title>

<assemblage><title>A Quick Refresher</title>
<p>Recall that an <term>exponent</term> is a number that appears above and to the right of a particular factor. It tells us how many times that factor occurs in the product. For example,
    <me>5^2 = 5 \times 5 = 25 ~~~~~~ \text{and} ~~~~~ 5^3 = 5 \times 5 \times 5 = 125</me>
You can review exponents in <xref ref="exponents" text="custom">Section 3.2</xref>.</p></assemblage>

<p>To <term>square</term> a number means to multiply the number by itself. For example,
    <me>7^2 = 7 \times 7 = 49</me>
If you know the square of a number, can you find the original number?</p>

<sidebyside widths="70% 25%"><stack><p>The area of the square shown at right is 25 square inches. What is the length of each side of the square? Because the area of a square is found by squaring the length of a side, we are looking for a number whose square is 25.</p>
<p>You can probably see that the number we need is 5, because <m>5^2 = 25</m>. The number 5 is called a <term>square root</term> of 25.</p></stack>  
  <image source="fivesquared.png"></image></sidebyside>

<assemblage><title>Definition</title>
<p>A number <m>s</m> is called a <term>square root</term> of <m>N</m>  if <m>s^2 = N</m>.</p></assemblage>

<example><statement><p><ol marker="a.">
  <li><p>3 is a square root of 9 because <m>3^2 = 9</m>.</p></li>
  <li><p>8  is a square root of  64  because <m>8^2 = 64</m>.</p></li>
  <li><p><m>\dfrac{2}{3}</m>  is a square root of <m>\dfrac{4}{9}</m> because  <m>\left(\dfrac{2}{3}\right)^2 = \dfrac{4}{9}</m>.</p></li>
</ol></p></statement></example>

<exercise><statement><p>What number is a square root of 16 ?</p></statement>

<answer><p>4</p></answer></exercise>

<note><p> If you know about negative numbers, you will have noticed that 5 is not the only square root of 25.  We can see that <m>-5</m>  is another square root of  25, because 
    <me>(-5)^2 = (-5) \cdot (-5) = 25</me>
In fact, every positive number has two square roots, one positive and one negative.  We'll learn more about negative numbers in the next lesson.</p></note>

<assemblage><title>Notation</title>
<p>We have a special symbol called a <term>radical sign</term>, <m>\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}</m>, to denote the positive square root of a number.  For example,
    <me>\sqrt{16}~~~~ \text{means} ~~~~ \text{"the positive square root of 16."}</me>
so <m>\sqrt{16} = 4.</m></p></assemblage>

<example><statement><p><ol marker="a." cols="2">
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{144} = 12</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{0} = 0</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{1} = 1</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{17^2} = 17</m></p></li></ol></p></statement></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Evaluate  <m>\sqrt{4}</m></p></statement>

<answer><p>2</p></answer></exercise>

<p>Numbers such as 16 and 25 are called <term>perfect squares</term> because they are the squares of whole numbers: 
    <me>16 = 4^2 ~~~~~~ \text{and} ~~~~~~ 25 = 5^2 </me> 
We met perfect squares in our work with exponents. So you already know the square roots of several numbers.</p>

