<subsection><title>Approximating Square Roots</title>

<p>The square roots of perfect squares are easy to find.  But how can we find the square roots of numbers like 3 or 5, which are not perfect squares?</p>
<p>You can use your calculator to find square roots, but before we do that, let's try to understand what happens.</p>

<activity><title>More Square Roots</title>

<p>We'll try to find the square root of  5  by the method of guessing and correcting.</p>

<p><m>\blert{\text{Step 1}}</m></p>
<p>Because <m>2^2 = 4 </m>, <m>~~~~~~~~~~\sqrt{5}~</m> must be bigger than 2</p>
<p>Because <m>3^2 = 9 </m>, <m>~~~~~~~~~~\sqrt{5}~</m> must be smaller than 3</p>
<p>So <m>\sqrt{5}</m> is a number between 2 and 3.</p>

<p><m>\blert{\text{Step 2}}</m></p>
<p>Let's guess 2.5 for <m>\sqrt{5}</m>. To check our guess, we can square  2.5  and see if we get  5:
  <me>(2.5)^2 = 6.25</me>
  So 2.5 is too big to be the square root of  5.</p>

<p><m>\blert{\text{Step 3}}</m></p>
<p>Check the squares of several other numbers between  2  and  2.5:
    <md><mrow>(2.1)^2 = 4.41</mrow>
        <mrow>(2.2)^2 = 4.84 ~~~~~~ \blert{\text{Smaller than 5.}}</mrow>
        <mrow>(2.3)^2 = 5.29 ~~~~~~ \blert{\text{Larger than 5.}}</mrow></md>
  From these values, we see that <m>\sqrt{5}</m>  must be between  2.2  and  2.3. </p>

<p><m>\blert{\text{Step 4}}</m></p>
<p>Use your calculator to find the squares of several numbers between 2.2 and 2.3, until you "capture" 5.</p>

<tabular halign="center" >                        
        <row >
            <cell><m>(2.21)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.26)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row> 
            <cell><m>(2.22)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.27)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row> 
            <cell><m>(2.23)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.28)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row> 
            <cell><m>(2.24)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.29)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row>
            <cell><m>(2.25)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell></cell></row>                 
    </tabular>

<p>You should have discovered that <m>(2.23)^2</m>  is too small, and <m>(2.24)^2</m>  is too big. Therefore, <m>\sqrt{5}</m>  is a number between  2.23  and  2.24.</p>

<p><m>\blert{\text{Step 5}}</m></p>
<p>Use your calculator to capture 5 between two squares.</p>

<tabular halign="center" >                        
        <row >
            <cell><m>(2.231)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.236)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row> 
            <cell><m>(2.232)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.237)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row> 
            <cell><m>(2.233)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.238)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row> 
            <cell><m>(2.234)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell><m>(2.239)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell></row>
        <row>
            <cell><m>(2.235)^2 = <fillin characters="10"/></m></cell>
            <cell></cell></row>                 
    </tabular>

<p>You should have discovered that <m>(2.236)^2</m>  is too small, and <m>(2.237)^2</m>  is too big. Therefore, <m>\sqrt{5}</m> is a number between  2.236  and  2.237.</p>
</activity>

<p>Perhaps you think that  2.236  is close enough, and you don't want to fill in any more tables.  But maybe you are curious to know how far we have to go to find the exact decimal value of <m>\sqrt{5}</m>.</p>

<p>It turns out that no matter how many decimal places we find, we will never obtain an exact decimal form for <m>\sqrt{5}</m>.  For this reason, <m>\sqrt{5}</m> is called an <term>irrational number</term>, because it cannot be expressed as a decimal fraction.</p>

<assemblage><title>Definition</title>
<p>An <term>irrational number</term> is one that cannot be written as a fraction.</p></assemblage>

<note><sidebyside widths="60% 30%"><p>Do you think it's strange that some numbers cannot be written as fractions? So did the Pythagoreans. Hippasus, one of Pythagoras' students, proved that <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is irrational, and legend has it that they threw him overboard into the ocean.</p>
    <image source="hippasus.png"></image></sidebyside></note>

<p>There is nothing special about <m>\sqrt{5}</m>.  All whole numbers that are not perfect squares have square roots that are irrational.  However, by increasing the number of decimal places, we can find an approximation to <m>\sqrt{5}</m>, or to any irrational number, as accurate as we like.  For example,
    <me>\sqrt{5} \approx 2.2360679774998â€¦</me>
But there is no symbol to write the exact value of <m>\sqrt{5}</m> except for <m>\sqrt{5}</m> !</p>

<p>Most scientific calculators give values for square roots to as many digits as their displays allow. Look for a key labeled <m>\boxed{\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}}</m>,  and enter
  <me> 5 \hphantom{0} \boxed{\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}}</me>
(On a graphing calculator, enter the radical symbol first: <m>\boxed{\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}} \hphantom{0} 5</m>.)  The calculator will return an approximation for <m>\sqrt{5}</m>, for example, 2.236068. You can then round off the number to as many decimal places as you need.</p>

<note><p>You can review rounding in <xref ref="rounding"/>.</p></note>

<example><statement><p>Use a calculator to find approximate values for each square root. Round your answers to three decimal places.</p>
<p><ol marker="a." cols="3">
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{3}</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{243}</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\sqrt{0.02}</m></p></li>
</ol></p></statement>

<solution><p><ol marker="a.">
  <li><p>Enter <m> 3 \hphantom{0} \boxed{\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}}</m>, and the calculator displays  1.7320508. Rounding to three decimal places gives  1.732.</p></li>
  <li><p>Enter  <m>243 \hphantom{0} \boxed{\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}}</m>,  and the calculator displays  15.588457. Rounding to three decimal places gives  15.588.</p></li>
  <li><p>Enter <m>0.02 \hphantom{0} \boxed{\sqrt{\hphantom{0}}}</m>,  and the calculator displays  0.1414214. Rounding to three decimal places gives  0.141.</p></li>
</ol></p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Use a calculator to approximate <m>\sqrt{226}</m> to three decimal places.</p></statement>

<answer><m>15.033</m></answer></exercise>

</subsection>

<subsection><title>Squares and Square Roots</title>

<p>If you know that the square of an unknown positive number is 36, can you find the number?  Let's call the unknown number <m>n</m>.  In math notation, the question becomes:  can you find <m>n</m> if you know that
        <me>n^2 = 36</me> 
Of course you can: <m>n</m>  must be the square root of 36, or
        <me>n = \sqrt{36} = 6</me>
This is because squaring and taking square roots are <term>opposite operations</term>;  each operation undoes the effects of the other.  If you square a number and then take the square root of the result, you get back to the original number.
    <me>\blert{\large\substack{\text{Start with} \\ \text{a Number}}  13  \rightarrow  \large\substack{\text{Square the} \\ \text{Number}}  \rightarrow  169  \rightarrow \large\substack{\text{Take the}\\ \text{Square Root}} \rightarrow  13 \hphantom{0} \large\substack{\text{Get the original}\\ \text{number back!}}}</me></p>

<example><statement><p>If <m>B</m> is a positive number and <m>B^2 = 784</m>,  what is the value of <m>B</m>?</p></statement>

<solution><p> <m>B</m> must be the square root of 784, or <m>B = \sqrt{784}</m>.  Using a calculator, we find that
    <me>B = \sqrt{784} = 28</me>
We can check our result by squaring.
    <me>B^2 = 28^2 = 784</me></p></solution></example>

<note><p>In Example 4.3.9, we can also say that we solved the equation <m>B^2 = 784</m>. Earlier we learned that we solve equations by applying opposite operations, and the same is true here:  to solve an equation where the variable is squared, we take the square root.</p></note>

<exercise><statement><p>If <m>p</m> is a positive number, solve the equation  <m>p^2 = 0.0225</m>.</p></statement>

<answer><m>p = 0.15</m></answer></exercise>
</subsection>

<subsection><title>Pythagorean Theorem</title>

<p>You probably remember the Pythagorean Theorem about the sides of a right triangle. Recall that a <term>right triangle</term> is one with a right, or ninety degree, angle. The side opposite the right angle is called the <term>hypotenuse</term>, and the other two sides are the <term>legs</term>.</p>

<assemblage><title>Pythagorean Theorem</title>
<p><sidebyside widths="60% 30%"><p>If the letter <m>\alert{c}</m> stands for the length of the hypotenuse, and the lengths of the two legs are denoted by <m>\alert{a}</m> and <m>\alert{b}</m>, then
  <me>\alert{a^2 + b^2 = c^2}</me></p>
<image source="Pythtri.png"></image></sidebyside></p></assemblage>
 
<p>We first studied the Pythagorean Theorem in <xref ref="pythagoras" text="custom">Section 3.2</xref>. And now that we can take square roots, we can use the theorem to solve problems.</p>

<example><statement><sidebyside widths="70% 25%"><p>The two legs of a right triangle are 6 inches and 8 inches long. How long is the hypotenuse?</p>
    <image source="six8rttri.png"></image></sidebyside></statement>

<solution><p>We substitute the lengths of the two legs into the Pythagorean theorem for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
    <md><mrow>6^2 + 8^2 \amp = c^2  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Compute the powers.}}</mrow>
        <mrow>36 + 64 \amp = c^2  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Add.}}</mrow>
        <mrow>100 \amp = c^2  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Take square roots.}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\sqrt{100} \amp = c  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Simplify the radical.}}</mrow>
        <mrow>10 \amp = c</mrow></md>
The hypotenuse is 10 inches long.</p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>The two short sides of a right triangle are 9 meters and 40 meters. What is the length of the hypotenuse?</p></statement>

<answer><p>41 meters</p></answer></exercise>

<example><statement><sidebyside widths="70% 25%"><p>A triathlete wants to know the distance across a small lake, from point <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>.  She locates point <m>C</m> on one side of the lake to make a right triangle as shown. The distance from <m>A</m> to <m>C</m> is 3 miles, and the distance from <m>B</m> to <m>C</m> is 4 miles.  How far is it from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> across the lake?</p>
    <image source="laketri.png"></image></sidebyside></statement>

<solution><p>We can apply the Pythagorean theorem. Let's let <m>d</m> represent the distance across the lake, from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>.  Then
    <me>d^2 + 3^2 = 4^2</me>
We square the numbers to get
    <me>d^2+ 9 = 16</me>
If 9 added to <m>d^2</m> gives 16, then <m>d^2</m> must be equal to 7.
    <me>d^2 = 7</me>
So <m>d</m> must be the square root of 7.
    <me>d = \sqrt{7} = 2.64575 ...</me>
The distance across the lake is about 2.65 miles.</p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><sidebyside widths="70% 30%"><p>The Department of Roads wants to know the distance through a mountain in the path of a proposed highway from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>. The field engineer locates point <m>C</m> on a line perpendicular to the planned route.  He then measures the distance from <m>A</m> to <m>C</m> as 2 miles, and the distance from <m>B</m> to <m>C</m> as 3 miles.  How far is it from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> through the mountain?</p>
     <image source="roadstri.png"></image></sidebyside></statement>

<answer><p>About 2.24 miles</p></answer></exercise>

