<activity><title>Spiral of Roots</title>

<sidebyside widths="60% 35%"><stack><p>The figure at the start of this section is called the Spiral of Theodorus. Theodorus of Cyrene was a Greek mathematician who lived in the 5th century BCE. He used the spiral to prove that the square roots of the non-square numbers up to 17 are irrational.</p>

<p>To make the spiral, you start with the right triangle shaded in blue. Then you use the hypotenuse of that triangle as one leg of another right triangle, with a second leg of length 1. Continue the process, adding a new right triangle at each step.</p></stack>
  <image source="bluespiral.png"></image></sidebyside>

<p><ol>
  <li><p>Use the Pythagorean theorem to find the hypotenuse of the first right triangle, shaded blue in the figure.</p></li>

  <li><p>Using your answer to part 1, find the hypotenuse of the second right triangle.</p></li>

  <li><p>Continue to find the hypotenuse of each right triangle in the figure.  Do you see a pattern?</p></li>
</ol></p></activity>

